---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

export const meta = {
  title: 'Hong Kong Police Now Empowered to Demand Phone Passwords Under Sweeping New Security Rules',
  description: 'Under an amended National Security Law, Hong Kong police can legally force suspects to hand over their phone and computer passwords, carrying severe jail sentences and heavy fines for non-compliance.',
  category: 'tech',
  published: '2026-03-24',
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "NewsArticle",
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "datePublished": meta.published,
  "dateModified": meta.published,
  "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Trunk Press" },
  "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Trunk Press" },
  "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://trunkpress.photonbuilder.com/hk-police-can-now-demand-phone-passwords-under" }
};
---

<SiteLayout site="trunkpress" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://trunkpress.photonbuilder.com/hk-police-can-now-demand-phone-passwords-under" schema={schema}>
  <article class="tp-article max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 py-12">
    <!-- Category + Date -->
    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
      <span class="text-xs font-black tracking-[2px] uppercase text-[var(--accent-color)]">⚡ TECH</span>
      <span class="text-xs text-[var(--text-secondary)]">March 24, 2026</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Headline -->
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black leading-tight mb-4 text-[var(--text-primary)]">
      Hong Kong Police Now Empowered to Demand Phone Passwords Under Sweeping New Security Rules
    </h1>

    <!-- Lede -->
    <p class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed mb-8 border-l-4 border-[var(--accent-color)] pl-4">
      Under an amended National Security Law, Hong Kong authorities can now legally force suspects to hand over their mobile phone and computer passwords. Refusing to comply carries up to a year in prison and a fine of HK$100,000.
    </p>

    <!-- Article body -->
    <div class="space-y-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] mt-8 mb-3">What Happened</h2>
      <p>
        The Hong Kong government has published controversial new amendments to the Beijing-imposed National Security Law, bypassing the city’s legislature to grant sweeping new surveillance powers to law enforcement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Under the updated rules, police are now authorized to demand any password or decryption method for electronic devices from individuals suspected of endangering national security. The provision strictly requires targets to provide "any reasonable and necessary information or assistance" to authorities.
      </p>
      <p>
        The amendments also empower customs officers to seize physical or digital items deemed to carry a "seditious intention," regardless of whether any formal arrest has taken place.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] mt-8 mb-3">The Penalties</h2>
      <p>
        The cost of defiance under the newly implemented law is steep. Individuals who refuse to surrender their device passcodes or decryption keys face up to one year in jail and a fine of HK$100,000 (roughly $12,700 or £9,600).
      </p>
      <p>
        Furthermore, attempting to deceive authorities carries an even heavier burden. Providing false or misleading information to police officers seeking access to a device is punishable by up to three years’ imprisonment and a massive fine of up to HK$500,000.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] mt-8 mb-3">Why It Matters</h2>
      <p>
        These new powers represent a significant escalation in the ongoing crackdown on dissent within the financial hub. Legal scholars and privacy advocates warn that the broad provisions strip away fundamental liberties, including the privacy of personal communications and the right against self-incrimination.
      </p>
      <p>
        Critics point out that these sweeping powers are granted to law enforcement without the need for prior judicial authorization or independent oversight. A Hong Kong government spokesperson, however, defended the changes, stating they conform to the city’s human rights provisions and "will not affect the lives of the general public or the normal operation of institutions and organisations."
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] mt-8 mb-3">The Bigger Picture</h2>
      <p>
        The original National Security Law, implemented by Beijing in 2020 following months of massive pro-democracy protests, fundamentally altered Hong Kong's political landscape. Since its inception, 386 people have been arrested for national security crimes, resulting in 176 individual convictions alongside four companies.
      </p>
      <p>
        With these new amendments, the line between personal digital privacy and state security has been all but erased for anyone falling under suspicion. As authorities tighten their grip on digital communications, the chilling effect on journalists, activists, and everyday citizens in Hong Kong continues to deepen.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Tags -->
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-10 pt-6 border-t border-[var(--border-color)]">
      <span class="text-xs bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded px-3 py-1 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">#HongKong</span>
      <span class="text-xs bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded px-3 py-1 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">#NationalSecurity</span>
      <span class="text-xs bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded px-3 py-1 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">#Privacy</span>
      <span class="text-xs bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded px-3 py-1 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">#TechNews</span>
      <span class="text-xs bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded px-3 py-1 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">#Censorship</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Related -->
    <div class="mt-8 p-5 bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded">
      <h3 class="text-sm font-black tracking-wider text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">RELATED STORIES</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]">More coverage coming. This is a developing story.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>
